```cpp
#include <hexi/hexi.h>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <cstdint>

struct NetworkPacket {
    uint32_t packet_id;
    std::string username;
    std::vector<uint32_t> scores;
    std::string metadata;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        // Write packet_id directly
        stream & packet_id;

        // Write username with length prefix
        stream & hexi::prefixed(username);

        // Write scores: count first, then elements using operator<<
        uint32_t count = static_cast<uint32_t>(scores.size());
        stream & count;
        stream << scores;

        // Write metadata as null-terminated string
        stream & hexi::null_terminated(metadata);
    }
};

std::vector<uint8_t> serialize_packet(const NetworkPacket& packet) {
    std::vector<uint8_t> buffer;
    hexi::buffer_adaptor adaptor(buffer);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(adaptor);

    // Serialize the packet using its serialise method
    const_cast<NetworkPacket&>(packet).serialise(stream);

    return buffer;
}
```

The implementation:

1. **`serialise` method**:
   - Uses `stream & packet_id` to write the packet ID directly
   - Uses `hexi::prefixed(username)` to write the username with automatic length prefix
   - Manually writes the scores count, then uses `operator<<` with the scores vector to write elements
   - Uses `hexi::null_terminated(metadata)` to write the metadata string with null terminator

2. **`serialize_packet` function**:
   - Creates a `std::vector<uint8_t>` buffer to hold the serialized data
   - Wraps it with `hexi::buffer_adaptor` 
   - Creates a `hexi::binary_stream` for serialization
   - Calls the `serialise` method on the packet (using `const_cast` since the method is bidirectional)
   - Returns the populated buffer

