# Complete Implementation

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<std::endian from, std::endian to, typename T>
T convert_endianness(T value) {
    return hexi::conditional_reverse<from, to>(value);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_endianness_runtime(T value, std::endian from, std::endian to) {
    if (from == std::endian::little && to == std::endian::big) {
        return hexi::conditional_reverse<std::endian::little, std::endian::big>(value);
    } else if (from == std::endian::big && to == std::endian::little) {
        return hexi::conditional_reverse<std::endian::big, std::endian::little>(value);
    } else if (from == std::endian::little && to == std::endian::little) {
        return hexi::conditional_reverse<std::endian::little, std::endian::little>(value);
    } else { // from == std::endian::big && to == std::endian::big
        return hexi::conditional_reverse<std::endian::big, std::endian::big>(value);
    }
}
```

## Explanation

1. **`convert_endianness`**: This is a compile-time endianness conversion function. It uses the Hexi library's `conditional_reverse` template function with the compile-time `from` and `to` endianness parameters to perform the conversion.

2. **`convert_endianness_runtime`**: This is a runtime endianness conversion function. Since `conditional_reverse` requires compile-time template parameters, we need to check all possible runtime combinations of `from` and `to` endianness values and dispatch to the appropriate compile-time instantiation. The function handles all four cases:
   - Little to Big
   - Big to Little  
   - Little to Little (no conversion)
   - Big to Big (no conversion)

The Hexi library's `conditional_reverse` will automatically handle byte swapping only when necessary (i.e., when `from != to`), making these functions efficient.

