# Complete Solution

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct UserData {
    uint32_t user_id;
    std::string name;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        stream << user_id << name;
    }
};

void serialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const UserData& data) {
    const_cast<UserData&>(data).serialise(writer);
}

void deserialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader, UserData& data) {
    reader >> data.user_id >> data.name;
}
```

## Explanation:

1. **`serialize_object`**: Since the `serialise()` method is not const-qualified (as it needs to work for both serialization and deserialization), we use `const_cast` to call it on the const `UserData&` parameter. The method then uses the `<<` operator to write the data to the writer stream.

2. **`deserialize_object`**: For deserialization, we use the `>>` operator to read data from the reader stream into the `UserData` object's fields. Since `serialise()` uses `<<` (write-only operator), we directly use `>>` for reading.

**Note**: For a more robust implementation that truly uses the same `serialise()` method for both operations, you could modify `UserData::serialise()` to use the bidirectional syntax shown in the examples:

```cpp
void serialise(auto& stream) {
    stream(user_id, name);  // or: stream & user_id & name;
}
```

This would allow both functions to simply call `data.serialise(stream)` without const_cast or manual field access.

