Looking at the code fragments and the Hexi library patterns, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>

void skip_bytes_in_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, std::size_t bytes) {
    buffer.skip(bytes);
}

struct MessageHeader {
    uint16_t message_type;
    uint32_t body_length;
};

MessageHeader read_header_and_skip_body(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    MessageHeader header;

    // Read message_type (2 bytes)
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(&header.message_type), sizeof(header.message_type));

    // Read body_length (4 bytes)
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(&header.body_length), sizeof(header.body_length));

    // Skip the body data based on the length field
    buffer.skip(header.body_length);

    return header;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`skip_bytes_in_buffer`**: Uses the `skip()` method provided by the `buffer_adaptor` to advance the read position by the specified number of bytes without actually reading the data.

